THOUGHT: The AddressSanitizer report clearly indicates a stack-buffer-overflow in the `crc8` function. The overflow occurs at `buf[i]` when `i == len`, which is one past the end of the `buf` array. The loop condition `for (size_t i = 0; i <= len; i++)` is incorrect — it should be `i < len` to avoid accessing `buf[len]`, which is out of bounds. The `buf` array has 7 elements (indices 0 to 6), but the loop runs to `i == 7`, causing a read of memory beyond the array. This is a classic off-by-one error. The `len` passed is `sizeof(buf)`, which is 7, so the loop runs 8 times instead of 7. The sanitizer confirms the access is at offset 39 in the stack frame, which is just beyond the 7-byte `buf` array (32 to 39). The root cause is a loop condition that includes an out-of-bounds index.

ROOT CAUSE: In `program.c` at line 12, the `crc8` function uses a loop condition `i <= len`, which causes the loop to access `buf[len]` when `i == len`. Since `buf` has `len` elements (indices 0 to `len-1`), accessing `buf[len]` is a buffer overflow. This is a classic off-by-one error where the loop runs one iteration too many.

LOCAL FIX: Change the loop condition from `i <= len` to `i < len` in the `crc8` function to ensure only valid array indices are accessed.

```c
for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
    crc ^= buf[i];
    for (int b = 0; b < 8; b++) {
        crc = (crc & 0x80) ? (uint8_t)((crc << 1) ^ 0x07) : (uint8_t)(crc << 1);
    }
}
```

GLOBAL FIX: Replace the raw array and size parameter with a bounded view type (e.g., `struct buffer_view`) that enforces bounds at compile time. This prevents out-of-bounds access by design. For example, define a `buffer_view` struct with a pointer and length, and use it in `crc8` to ensure safe access. This eliminates the possibility of off-by-one errors by making the bounds explicit and checked at the API level.

